metadata.title: Piper PA-18 Super Cub
aws::graph::propositions: # Piper PA-18 Super Cub Design and Development
Piper PA-18 Super Cub is based on the design of earlier Cubs.
Piper PA-18 Super Cub includes an electrical system.
Piper PA-18 Super Cub includes flaps with 3 notches.
Piper PA-18 Super Cub includes a considerably more powerful engine compared to earlier Cubs.
The standard Piper PA-18 Super Cub was fitted with a 150-horsepower Lycoming engine.
The Lycoming engine in the standard Piper PA-18 Super Cub produces 112 kW of power.
Piper PA-18 Super Cub is not uncommonly equipped with a 160-horsepower O-320-B2B Lycoming engine.
Piper PA-18 Super Cub is not uncommonly equipped with a 180-horsepower Lycoming O-360 powerplant.
The Lycoming O-360 powerplant produces 134 kW of power.
Piper PA-18 Super Cub has a high-lift wing.
Piper PA-18 Super Cub's high-lift wing and powerful engine made it a prime candidate for conversion to floatplane.
Piper PA-18 Super Cub's high-lift wing and powerful engine made it a prime candidate for conversion to skiplane.
PA-18A is an agricultural version of the Piper PA-18 Super Cub.
PA-18A was produced for applying dry chemical spray.
PA-18A was produced for applying liquid spray.
Piper PA-18 Super Cub retained the basic "rag and tube" structure of the earlier J-3 Cub.
"Rag and tube" structure consists of fabric stretched over a steel tube frame.

text:
## Design and development
While based on the design of the earlier Cubs, the addition of an electrical system, flaps (3 notches), and a considerably more powerful engine (150 hp), made it a very different flying experience. Although the "standard" Super Cub was fitted with a 150-horsepower (112 kW) Lycoming engine, it is not uncommon to see them equipped with a 160-horsepower O-320-B2B, or even 180 horsepower (134 kW) Lycoming O-360 powerplant. The high-lift wing and powerful engine made the Super Cub a prime candidate for conversion to either floatplane or skiplane.  In addition, the PA-18A (an agricultural version) was produced for applying either dry chemical or liquid spray.
The Super Cub retained the basic "rag and tube" (fabric stretched over a steel tube frame) structure of the earlier J-3 Cub.
